                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-298-off1623 t18300415-298-crimeloc1626"></join> - the prisoner was my apprentice for about twelve months; these books were found in his possession - he was attempting to sell them; I know they are mine - they are Sunday-school poems.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-298-person2509">
                  GEORGE 
                  DEVERELL
               <interp inst="t18300415-298-person2509" type="surname" value="DEVERELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-298-person2509" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-298-person2509" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am beadle of Shadwell. On the morning of the 10th of March, I was going along High-street, Shadwell, and saw the prisoner with something under his jacket - I went into the shop he came out of, and found he had been offering books for sale; I then went to an opposite house and looked through the window - I watched him for some time, and saw him go into a shop; I sent a person, and he was brought to me - he said he was going to sell them for his mother, who had a stock of them, and he was selling some for a breakfast; I took him to the watch-house, and sent for the prosecutor.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. My master used to go and stay out all hours of the night; he kept me at home at work on Sunday, instead of going to church, and gave me no money.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-298-person2510">
                  WILLIAM 
                  MYERS
               <interp inst="t18300415-298-person2510" type="surname" value="MYERS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-298-person2510" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-298-person2510" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I gave him money to go and see his mother, and he never went - I used to send him to church every Sunday with my sons.</p>
